{
  "masechta": "Zevachim",
  "daf": 84,
  "amud": "a",
  "macro_segments": [
    {
      "title": "Introduction and Overview of the Perek: The Altar Sanctifies Invalid Offerings",
      "display_title": "Altar Sanctifies",
      "timestamp": "00:00",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "The principle that the altar sanctifies things placed upon it despite invalidity",
          "display_title": "Principle Overview",
          "timestamp": "00:00"
        },
        {
          "title": "Discussion of what types of items connect to the altar and their eligibility",
          "display_title": "Types of Items",
          "timestamp": "00:22"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Mishna: Things That Do Not Come Down (Elu Im Alu Lo Yardu)",
      "display_title": "Elu Im Alu Lo Yardu",
      "timestamp": "01:17",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Introduction to the mishna and cases where things may stay on the altar despite post-slaughter problems",
          "display_title": "Cases Staying Up",
          "timestamp": "01:17"
        },
        {
          "title": "Cases of notar (overnight), yotzei (removed from sanctuary), and tamei (impure) items",
          "display_title": "Notar, Yotzei, Tamei",
          "timestamp": "01:24"
        },
        {
          "title": "Cases of improper slaughter: chutz lizmano, chutz limekomo, and when a pasul kohen handles the blood",
          "display_title": "Improper Slaughter Cases",
          "timestamp": "02:39"
        },
        {
          "title": "The concept of piggul and its relationship to validity despite invalid intent",
          "display_title": "Piggul Concept",
          "timestamp": "03:16"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Yehuda's three exceptions that must come down: slaughtered at night, blood spilled, blood exits the curtains",
          "display_title": "Rabbi Yehuda's Exceptions",
          "timestamp": "03:27"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Shimon's view that only truly kosher olot get to stay, using the word olah to include everything that goes up",
          "display_title": "Rabbi Shimon Position",
          "timestamp": "04:56"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Rabbi Shimon's Inclusive Approach and the Distinction Between Psuluto Bakodesh and Lo Hayah Psulo Bakodesh",
      "display_title": "Psuluto Bakodesh",
      "timestamp": "05:15",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Shimon's principle: if the invalidity occurred once the item was already in the kodesh, it gets accepted",
          "display_title": "Kodesh Accepts",
          "timestamp": "05:15"
        },
        {
          "title": "Items that were invalid before the kodesh: rove'ah, nirba, muktza, ne'evad, etnan, mechir, kilayim, treifa, yotzei dofen, ba'alei mumin",
          "display_title": "Invalid Before Kodesh",
          "timestamp": "06:08"
        },
        {
          "title": "The conceptual distinction: problems that are ritual failures versus problems that are inherent defects",
          "display_title": "Ritual vs. Defect",
          "timestamp": "07:35"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Akiva's lenient position on ba'alei mumin and its limitation in the gemara",
          "display_title": "Rabbi Akiva on Mumin",
          "timestamp": "09:15"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Chanina Sgan HaKohanim's testimony about actual practice: ba'alei mumin were pushed off the altar",
          "display_title": "Practice Testimony",
          "timestamp": "09:55"
        },
        {
          "title": "The principle of reciprocity: if something goes down, it cannot come back up",
          "display_title": "Reciprocity Principle",
          "timestamp": "10:54"
        },
        {
          "title": "Animal walking alive to top of altar and slaughtering on the altar: they come down regardless",
          "display_title": "Alive Animals",
          "timestamp": "11:18"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Gemara Discussion: Textual Basis for the Rule That Things Placed on Altar Stay There",
      "display_title": "Textual Basis",
      "timestamp": "13:10",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Baraita citing parashat olah: zot hi ha'olah as the source for things that go up staying up",
          "display_title": "Zot Hi Ha'olah",
          "timestamp": "13:10"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Yehuda's use of three limiting words: zot, hi, ha'olah to exclude three specific cases",
          "display_title": "Three Limiting Words",
          "timestamp": "13:50"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Shimon's alternative: focusing on the word torat as inclusive, allowing the exception to be drawn based on the kodesh principle",
          "display_title": "Torat as Inclusive",
          "timestamp": "14:37"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Shimon's principle expanded: inclusion and exclusion based on whether psul occurred in kodesh context",
          "display_title": "Shimon's Expansion",
          "timestamp": "15:00"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Rabbi Yehuda's Justification Through Analogy: Why Certain Invalidities Are Acceptable",
      "display_title": "Rabbi Yehuda Analogy",
      "timestamp": "19:32",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Yehuda's methodology: starting from exclusion and requiring justification for inclusion, not the reverse",
          "display_title": "Methodology Shift",
          "timestamp": "19:32"
        },
        {
          "title": "Notar stays because amurim or meat can sometimes be acceptable overnight (shlamim comparison)",
          "display_title": "Notar Analogy",
          "timestamp": "20:12"
        },
        {
          "title": "Yotzei stays because of bamah precedent allowing items outside the mikdash",
          "display_title": "Yotzei Analogy",
          "timestamp": "22:00"
        },
        {
          "title": "Tamei stays because public offerings (korban tzibbur) can be offered when tamei",
          "display_title": "Tamei Analogy",
          "timestamp": "22:40"
        },
        {
          "title": "Chutz lizmano stays because piggul concept keeps it in valid suspended reality",
          "display_title": "Chutz Lizmano Analogy",
          "timestamp": "22:53"
        },
        {
          "title": "Chutz limekomo stays by connection to chutz lizmano reasoning",
          "display_title": "Chutz Limekomo Analogy",
          "timestamp": "23:26"
        },
        {
          "title": "Kibel psulim by discussing only psulim acceptable for public offerings (tamei)",
          "display_title": "Kibel Psulim Analogy",
          "timestamp": "23:42"
        },
        {
          "title": "Gemara's critique: how can you compare invalid cases to valid cases when drawing analogy",
          "display_title": "Gemara Critique",
          "timestamp": "24:58"
        },
        {
          "title": "Gemara's resolution: tanna relies on zot torat ha'olah as umbrella, analogy merely identifies which psulim are meant",
          "display_title": "Resolution via Torat",
          "timestamp": "25:30"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Application: Bringing an Offering Outside the Mikdash and the Distinction Between Animals and Birds",
      "display_title": "Outside Mikdash",
      "timestamp": "27:40",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Yochanan's principle: shechita at night inside with offering brought outside is chayav",
          "display_title": "Night Inside, Out",
          "timestamp": "27:40"
        },
        {
          "title": "Reasoning: no worse than shechita outside and bringing up outside, should both be chayav",
          "display_title": "Comparative Logic",
          "timestamp": "29:40"
        },
        {
          "title": "Contradiction: mishna teaches shechita of bird inside then offering outside is patur",
          "display_title": "Bird Exception",
          "timestamp": "31:15"
        },
        {
          "title": "Resolution: bird shechita inside is not a meaningful shechita act (melikah required instead), unlike mammal",
          "display_title": "Melikah Issue",
          "timestamp": "32:58"
        },
        {
          "title": "Application to mammals: shechita at night inside is still a valid shechita act, making bringing outside chayav",
          "display_title": "Mammal Distinction",
          "timestamp": "34:00"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
